This was based on the 3.15 PR: https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/pull/43129/files

Fixes issue dotnet/runtime#57472

Main pr dotnet/runtime#57479

Also backported to 5.0 in dotnet/runtime#57562 and 3.1 in #43102. This PR will pave the way for backporting it to the `System.Memory` OOB package for .NET Framework.

# Customer Impact

A customer has encountered dotnet/runtime#57472 while on .NET Framework and reported it in dotnet/runtime#67295, necessiating backporting it once again. As an example provided in that issue, this memory manager:

``` csharp
private sealed class BasicMemoryManager : MemoryManager<byte>
{
    private readonly byte[] _buffer;
    public BasicMemoryManager(int size = 1024) => _buffer = new byte[size];

    protected override bool TryGetArray(out ArraySegment<byte> segment)
    {
        segment = new ArraySegment<byte>(_buffer);
        return true;
    }
    public override Span<byte> GetSpan() => _buffer;

    public override MemoryHandle Pin(int elementIndex = 0) => throw new NotSupportedException();
    public override void Unpin() => throw new NotSupportedException();
    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing) { }
}
```

will fail two of the following tests:

``` csharp
[Theory]
[InlineData(0, 32)]
[InlineData(0, 29)]
[InlineData(32, 32)] // fail: length 0
[InlineData(32, 29)] // fail: length -3
public void OffsetTest(int offset, int length)
{
    var mgr = new BasicMemoryManager(1024);
    var slice = mgr.Memory.Slice(offset, length);
    Assert.Equal(length, slice.Length);

    var ros = new ReadOnlySequence<byte>(slice);
    Assert.True(ros.IsSingleSegment);
    Assert.Equal(length, ros.Length);
}
```

# Testing

Failing test has been added in this PR.

# Risk

Low, as the change is very simple and obvious when you look at `ReadOnlySequence<T>` ctor that accepts `ReadOnlyMemory<T>` (notice line 133 versus lines 140 and 148):

https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/0d40b482e6b6c232131dc808182d6b32d9d37394/src/System.Memory/src/System/Buffers/ReadOnlySequence.cs#L130-L149

Moreover, the changed code gets triggered only when creating a `ReadOnlySequence` from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by a `MemoryManager`. All other use cases (including creating from an array or from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by an array or a string) are unaffected. And the changes are identical to those in the other backports.

# Regression

This is not a regression.

**Version Used**: VS17.11.2, LangVersion preview

**Steps to Reproduce**:

```csharp
    public ref struct RefAwaitable
    {
        public ref struct Awaiter : ICriticalNotifyCompletion, INotifyCompletion
        {
            public void UnsafeOnCompleted(Action continuation) => ThreadPool.UnsafeQueueUserWorkItem(_ => continuation(), null);
            public void OnCompleted(Action continuation) => ThreadPool.UnsafeQueueUserWorkItem(_ => continuation(), null);

            public bool IsCompleted => false;

            public int GetResult() => 114514;
        }

        public Awaiter GetAwaiter() => default;
    }

    internal class Program
    {
        static async Task Main(string[] args)
        {
            RefAwaitable r = default;
            Console.WriteLine(await r);
        }
    }
```

The code snippets errors for "RefAwaitable.Awaiter doesn't implement INotifyCompletion", though it can implement from C# 13. Since awaiter needs to be saved in state machine, it can't be ref struct.
Also, the ECMA C# 7.x spec doesn't call out that awaiter can't be ref struct. The spec may need to be updated together.

**Version Used**:  Visual Studio 2022 17.12 Preview 1.0

**Steps to Reproduce**:

Apply the code fix (IDE0066 Use 'switch' expression) suggested on the switch statement in the SaveAnimal method (complete Program.cs below):
```
var animal = GetAnimal();
SaveAnimal(animal);

static void SaveAnimal(Animal animal)
{
    ArgumentNullException.ThrowIfNull(animal);

    switch (animal)
    {
        case Dog dog:
            _ = SaveDog(dog);
            break;
        case Cat cat:
            _ = SaveCat(cat);
            break;
        default:
            throw new ArgumentException($"Unknown animal {animal.GetType()}");
    }
}

static Animal GetAnimal() => Random.Shared.Next(2) == 0 ? new Dog() : new Cat();

static Dog SaveDog(Dog dog) => dog;

static Cat SaveCat(Cat cat) => cat;

public class Animal
{
}

public class Dog : Animal
{
}

public class Cat : Animal
{
}
```

**Diagnostic Id**:IDE0066 Use 'switch' expression


**Expected Behavior**: Should produce code that compiles or not suggest the code fix

**Actual Behavior**: Generates code that fails due to CS8506 "No best type was found for the switch expression" due to the code fix producing the following code:

```
static void SaveAnimal(Animal animal)
{
    ArgumentNullException.ThrowIfNull(animal);

    _ = animal switch // <-- CS8506: _ type has to handle both Dog and Cat
    {
        Dog dog => SaveDog(dog),
        Cat cat => SaveCat(cat),
        _ => throw new ArgumentException($"Unknown animal {animal.GetType()}"),
    };
}
```

For the above to work the you either have to have:
```
    Animal _ = animal switch // or object _
    {
        Dog dog => SaveDog(dog),
        Cat cat => SaveCat(cat),
        _ => throw new ArgumentException($"Unknown animal {animal.GetType()}"),
    };
```

or

```
    _ = animal switch
    {
        Dog dog => (Animal)SaveDog(dog),
        Cat cat => (Animal)SaveCat(cat),
        _ => throw new ArgumentException($"Unknown animal {animal.GetType()}"),
    };
```
